item.title: Silver Linings
item.description: My grandma was well into her 90s, and I got to say goodbye to her while she still knew who I was. I miss her very much, and while she and I would butt heads on a great many things, she was instrumental in my love of nature, music, and the idea that family is more than blood. Family is a choice, and one that requires active intent and effort. We actively chose to be family in spite of genetics, not because of it. I've worked a very high stress job with few resources for almost a decade now, and the toll it has taken on my physical and mental health has gotten to the point where I have had multiple periods of coming REALLY close to ending things. I'm still not entirely out of my most recent bout. I already had a decent "oh shit" fund set aside from the salary I've been telling myself was worth the stress. Grandma left me a decent chunk of change, though, so I think that the gift I'm going to use that money for is peace. I'm setting the goal to be done with the current job by Valentine's Day. It's far enough out that I could conceivably find another option before then, but soon enough to be a tangible light at the end of the tunnel regardless of whether I've managed to line something up before then or not. Thanks, Grandma. You helped teach me that life wasn't for survival, and now I plan to use what you left to do more than survive.
